There are some good points in the replies about air-volume and more warm air entering an empty freezer when opened, but all things being equal, a single ice cube tray of water should freeze faster than five trays put in at once. Though the difference may not be super huge.

This also assumes that the freezer cools the interior at a constant rate. I could imagine a freezer that somehow 'detects' the job ahead and works harder (cools at a faster rate) if there's a large mass of un-frozen stuff inside suddenly.
If the freezer is full and everything inside is already as cold as the freezer gets, there shouldn't be much difference unless perhaps the freezer is so full that air flow is restricted.

The more stuff there is in the freezer that isnt already frozen, the longer it will take for everything in the freezer to freeze. Imagine a cup of water by itself vs a cup of water and a huge pot of hot oil. The oil will warm the space and slow the temp drop for everything inside
